Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/background.ts (add syncPreScripts to the three lifecycle entry points)

Context:
The POC wired syncPreScripts into handleSyncFull (called once per WebSocket connect) and handlePluginUpdate (called on plugin rebuilds). Neither fires on a plain extension reload from chrome://extensions/ or on a Chrome browser restart. Research confirmed (MDN RegisteredContentScript, and Chrome's scripting API guide): persistAcrossSessions survives browser restarts and SW restarts but NOT extension updates or manual extension reloads. The canonical fix is to re-register in the onInstalled handler.

Current code (lines 139-161 of background.ts):
```
chrome.runtime.onInstalled.addListener(() => {
  void (async () => {
    await ensureConnectionId();
    await ensureOffscreenDocument();
    await setupKeepaliveAlarm();
    await reinjectStoredPlugins();
  })().catch((err: unknown) => console.warn('[opentabs] onInstalled failed:', err));
});

chrome.runtime.onStartup.addListener(() => {
  void (async () => {
    await ensureConnectionId();
    await ensureOffscreenDocument();
    await setupKeepaliveAlarm();
    await reinjectStoredPlugins();
  })().catch((err: unknown) => console.warn('[opentabs] onStartup failed:', err));
});

ensureConnectionId()
  .then(() => ensureOffscreenDocument())
  .catch((err: unknown) => console.warn('[opentabs] offscreen creation failed:', err));
setupKeepaliveAlarm().catch((err: unknown) => console.warn('[opentabs] keepalive alarm failed:', err));
reinjectStoredPlugins().catch((err: unknown) => console.warn('[opentabs] plugin reinjection failed:', err));
```

Changes:
1. Add `import { syncPreScripts } from './pre-script-registration.js';` alongside the existing imports near the top of the file.
2. Add an import for `getAllPluginMeta` from './plugin-storage.js' if it's not already imported at the top of the file. (reinjectStoredPlugins internally uses it but doesn't export the list.)
3. In the onInstalled async IIFE, add `await syncPreScripts(Object.values(await getAllPluginMeta()));` after `await reinjectStoredPlugins();`.
4. In the onStartup async IIFE, do the same.
5. Below `reinjectStoredPlugins().catch(...)`, add a new top-level line: `(async () => { try { const metas = Object.values(await getAllPluginMeta()); await syncPreScripts(metas); } catch (err) { console.warn('[opentabs] pre-script registration failed:', err); } })();`

Constraints:
- Do NOT modify the existing pre-script registration in handleSyncFull (message-router.ts) or handlePluginUpdate — those remain the primary paths. The new calls are a safety net for cases where a plugin was previously stored but the WebSocket is not yet connected (extension reload, browser restart).
- Do NOT move existing await ensureConnectionId / ensureOffscreenDocument ordering. syncPreScripts must run AFTER reinjectStoredPlugins (adapter files and pre-script files live in the same adapters/ directory; reinjection may restore files).
- Do NOT call registerContentScripts directly — use the exported syncPreScripts helper which handles the diff/unregister of stale entries.
- Do NOT add a new chrome.runtime.onInstalled listener as a separate addListener() — extend the existing one so the ordering stays deterministic.

Trap warning: onInstalled.reason can be 'install', 'update', 'chrome_update', or 'shared_module_update'. Do NOT conditionally skip syncPreScripts based on reason — per MDN, even 'chrome_update' can reset registrations. Running syncPreScripts on every reason is idempotent (the diff inside unregisters stale first) and costs no more than a call to getRegisteredContentScripts.

Files:
- platform/plugin-tools/src/commands/build.ts (add isReady wrap in bundleIIFE wrapperCode)

Context:
The POC set globalThis.__openTabs._pluginName inside the tool.handle wrap so getPreScriptValue() called from within a tool handler targets the correct per-plugin bucket. But isReady() runs outside that wrap (it's called by the adapter runtime infrastructure, not through tool.handle). If an adapter's isReady wants to check whether the pre-script captured an auth token (a natural use — 'ready when token is present'), getPreScriptValue returns undefined because _pluginName has not been set yet.

Current tool-handle wrap (lines 868-891 of build.ts, inside the bundleIIFE wrapperCode template literal):
```
for (const tool of plugin.tools) {
  const origHandle = tool.handle;
  tool.handle = async function(...handleArgs: [unknown, ...unknown[]]) {
    const startTime = performance.now();
    // Pin the current plugin name so getPreScriptValue() in the SDK reads
    // this plugin's bucket, not another adapter's.
    const runtime = globalThis.__openTabs!;
    runtime._pluginName = ${name};
    ...
```

The wrapperCode is a big template literal that's concatenated and written to a temp .ts file, then bundled by esbuild.

Changes:
Insert the following block inside the wrapperCode string, just BEFORE the `const hasLifecycleHooks = ...` line at line 867 of build.ts:
```
// Wrap isReady to pin the current plugin name so getPreScriptValue() in the
// SDK reads this plugin's bucket even when called outside of tool.handle.
if (typeof plugin.isReady === 'function') {
  const origIsReady = plugin.isReady.bind(plugin);
  plugin.isReady = async function() {
    const runtime = globalThis.__openTabs!;
    runtime._pluginName = ${name};
    return await origIsReady();
  };
}
```

Constraints:
- Do NOT wrap onActivate, onDeactivate, onNavigate, onToolInvocationStart, onToolInvocationEnd, or teardown. Those hooks running concurrently across plugins could race on _pluginName; scope this change to isReady which the platform calls serially per plugin.
- Do NOT remove or modify the existing _pluginName line inside tool.handle — tool handlers and isReady need independent pins (tool.handle sets it per call; this wrap sets it per readiness probe).
- Do NOT assume plugin.isReady is always defined — the OpenTabsPlugin base class marks it abstract, but a misbehaving third-party plugin might not implement it. The typeof check guards against a TypeError at wrap time.
- Preserve the existing template literal structure — the ${name} interpolation uses the outer const `name = JSON.stringify(pluginName)` defined at the top of bundleIIFE (line 725).

Related code to read (do NOT modify): platform/plugin-sdk/src/pre-script-reader.ts — getPreScriptValue reads globalThis.__openTabs._pluginName and indexes into globalThis.__openTabs.preScript[_pluginName][key]. If _pluginName is undefined, it returns undefined; that is the bug this story fixes.

Trap warning: Do NOT await the origIsReady call without a try/finally — the caller (tool-dispatch or the extension's readiness poll) expects an awaitable that propagates errors, not a try/catch that swallows them. The minimal wrap above preserves error propagation via the `return await` pattern.

Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/message-router.ts (extend handlePluginUpdate with conditional tab reload)

Context:
registerContentScripts takes effect only on future navigations — tabs open at registration time keep running the pre-existing page JS (or nothing, if the pre-script was just added). When a plugin updates (plugin.update notification from the MCP server), users expect the new pre-script behavior to apply to their currently-open tabs without manual reload. Doing this on plugin.update is the right place because it's user-triggered (opentabs-plugin build calls POST /reload). Doing this on sync.full would cause a reload storm on every WebSocket reconnect (which happens on server restart, hot reload, secret rotation, and many other non-user-facing events).

Current code (lines 570-600 of message-router.ts):
```
const handlePluginUpdate = async (params: Record<string, unknown>): Promise<void> => {
  const validated = validatePluginPayload(params);
  if (!validated) return;

  const meta = toPluginMeta(validated);

  await storePluginsBatch([meta]);
  // Re-register (or register for the first time) the pre-script so matching
  // tabs injected on future navigations get the updated content.
  await upsertPreScript(meta);
  // Force re-injection so the new IIFE overwrites the stale adapter code
  // already present in matching tabs. Without this, injectPluginIntoMatchingTabs
  // skips tabs where the adapter is already injected, leaving old code running.
  await injectPluginIntoMatchingTabs(
    meta.name,
    meta.urlPatterns,
    ...
  );
```

Changes:
1. At the top of handlePluginUpdate, before `await storePluginsBatch([meta]);`, read the existing stored metadata:
```
  const existingIndex = await getAllPluginMeta();
  const existingMeta = existingIndex[meta.name];
  const preScriptChanged = meta.preScriptFile !== undefined &&
    (!existingMeta || existingMeta.preScriptHash !== meta.preScriptHash);
```
2. After `await upsertPreScript(meta);` and BEFORE the injectPluginIntoMatchingTabs call, add:
```
  if (preScriptChanged) {
    try {
      const tabIds: number[] = [];
      for (const pattern of meta.urlPatterns) {
        const tabs = await chrome.tabs.query({ url: pattern });
        for (const tab of tabs) {
          if (typeof tab.id === 'number') tabIds.push(tab.id);
        }
      }
      const unique = Array.from(new Set(tabIds));
      await Promise.allSettled(
        unique.map(id =>
          chrome.tabs.reload(id).catch((err: unknown) => {
            console.warn(`[opentabs] tab.reload failed for tabId=${String(id)}:`, err);
          }),
        ),
      );
    } catch (err) {
      console.warn('[opentabs] pre-script tab reload flow failed:', err);
    }
  }
```

Constraints:
- Do NOT reload tabs in handleSyncFull. That path fires on every WebSocket reconnect.
- Do NOT reload tabs when the adapter hash changes but preScriptHash is unchanged — adapter re-injection handles that case via the existing injectPluginIntoMatchingTabs call which forces re-injection.
- Do NOT reload tabs when the plugin never had a pre-script and still doesn't — the guard `meta.preScriptFile !== undefined` prevents that.
- The reload must happen AFTER upsertPreScript registers the new content script, otherwise the reloaded tab could fire before registration completes and not receive the script.
- Do NOT add a user confirmation dialog. The reload is part of the plugin update flow, which is already user-triggered by running `opentabs-plugin build`.
- Do NOT try to preserve tab scroll position or form state — Chrome's chrome.tabs.reload does not support that, and it's out of scope.

Related code to read (do NOT modify): platform/browser-extension/src/iife-injection.ts queryMatchingTabs helper — exists but takes excludePatterns as a second argument, which our case also needs. Consider using it instead of rolling a new tabs.query loop. Sample existing usage: `const matched = await queryMatchingTabs(meta.urlPatterns, meta.excludePatterns);` — each entry is `{ tabId, url }`. If you switch to this helper, import it from './iife-injection.js' (it is already exported alongside injectPluginIntoMatchingTabs).

Trap warning: chrome.tabs.reload returns Promise<void>, NOT a fulfilled tab object. Using the result as a truthy check is a bug. Use .catch for errors, don't inspect the resolved value.
